04319nam a22005295i 9780226234557DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014026787  a97802262345577 a10.7208/97802262345572doi  a(DE-B1597)550164  a(OCoLC)1229160896  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJK516b.D793 2015 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aDruckman, James N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWho Governs? :bPresidents, Public Opinion, and Manipulation /cLawrence R. Jacobs, James N. Druckman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b1 figure, 15 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Political Representation and Presidential Manipulation -- tChapter 1. Presidential Crafted Talk and Democratic Theory -- tChapter 2. The Political Strategy of Tracking the Public -- tPart II . Presidential Strategies to Shape Public Opinion -- tChapter 3. How White House Strategy Drives the Collection and Use of Its Polling -- tChapter 4. Segmented Representation -- tChapter 5. Elite Strategies to Prime Issues and Image -- tPart III. America’s Democratic Dilemmas -- tChapter 6. The Effects and Limits of Presidential Efforts to Move Public Opinion -- tChapter 7. Rethinking Representation -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerica’s model of representational government rests on the premise that elected officials respond to the opinions of citizens. This is a myth, however, not a reality, according to James N. Druckman and Lawrence R. Jacobs. In Who Governs?, Druckman and Jacobs combine existing research with novel data from US presidential archives to show that presidents make policy by largely ignoring the views of most citizens in favor of affluent and well-connected political insiders. Presidents treat the public as pliable, priming it to focus on personality traits and often ignoring it on policies that fail to become salient. Melding big debates about democratic theory with existing research on American politics and innovative use of the archives of three modern presidents—Johnson, Nixon, and Reagan—Druckman and Jacobs deploy lively and insightful analysis to show that the conventional model of representative democracy bears little resemblance to the actual practice of American politics. The authors conclude by arguing that polyarchy and the promotion of accelerated citizen mobilization and elite competition can improve democratic responsiveness. An incisive study of American politics and the flaws of representative government, this book will be warmly welcomed by readers interested in US politics, public opinion, democratic theory, and the fecklessness of American leadership and decision-making.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aJacobs, Lawrence R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226234557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226234557.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles